The dialog is created by the `ShellMountPasswordDialog` class inside `js/ui/shellMountOperation.js`. For testing purposes I have added some log messages to the event handler functions of the Cancel and Unlock buttons. It turns out that even in the case of auto-mounting when the dialog erroneously remains open after any button clicks, the bind works and the event handler functions will be called properly.

That error message from MountOpReply2 that was already mentioned before, only occurs if the Cancel button is pressed more than once. I would say that's expected, because the mount operation is already cancelled then:
```
gnome-shell[893]: ShellMountPasswordDialog - cancel button clicked
gnome-shell[893]: ShellMountPasswordDialog - cancel button clicked
gnome-shell[893]: Error from MountOpReply2(): GDBus.Error:org.gtk.Private.RemoteVolumeMonitor.NotFound: No outstanding mount operation
```

After applying the following patch to call the dialogs close method directly in the callbacks of the Cancel and Unlock buttons, the mounting of my encrypted device fully works for me in case of auto-mount and in case of manually mounting via nautilus.

```
--- shellMountOperation.js	2018-10-04 15:26:31.508661764 +0200
+++ shellMountOperation.js	2018-10-04 15:28:11.919233300 +0200
@@ -361,10 +361,12 @@

     _onCancelButton() {
         this.emit('response', -1, '', false);
+        this.close();
     },

     _onUnlockButton() {
         this._onEntryActivate();
+        this.close();
     },

     _onEntryActivate() {
```

Thus, there seems to be a difference in the handling after the response signal is emitted by `this.emit('response', ...` inside the callbacks of the buttons. In the case of auto-mount this does not trigger a close or destroy event for the dialog, whereas that correctly happens when the dialog is opened by manually mounting a device via nautilus.

There's also another difference (seen after applying the patch; don't know if that was also the case in Gnome 3.28) between auto-mount and manually mounting, when no password or a wrong password is entered before pressing the Unlock button. In case of manually mounting via nautilus a graphical error message dialog is shown, whereas at auto-mounting the error messages will only be written to the journal, e.g.:
```
gnome-shell[891]: Unable to mount volume 500 GB encrypted: Gio.IOErrorEnum: Error unlocking /dev/sdc1: Failed to activate device: Operation not permitted
gnome-shell[891]: Unable to mount volume 500 GB encrypted: Gio.IOErrorEnum: No key available to unlock device /dev/sdc1
```

I had a deeper look at this. The auto-mount case is handled by `ShellMountOperation._onAskPassword` method, whereas the manual mount is handled by `GnomeShellMountOpHandler.AskPasswordAsync` method.

From my point of view, the event handler function connected to the response signal in the `_onAskPassword` method is missing a call to close the dialog after one of the buttons is clicked. The other methods of the `ShellMountOperation` class like `_onAskQuestion` and `_onShowProcesses2` also calls `close()` inside the response event handler.

Adding this call of the close method with the following patch fully solves this issue for me:
```
--- shellMountOperation.js	2018-10-04 18:53:05.898001000 +0200
+++ shellMountOperation.js	2018-10-04 19:46:03.779912271 +0200
@@ -171,6 +171,8 @@
                     this.mountOp.set_password(password);
                     this.mountOp.reply(Gio.MountOperationResult.HANDLED);
                 }
+
+                this.close();
             });
         this._dialog.open();
     },
```

